  "prompt": "How can evaporated milk be substituted for condensed milk?",
  "response": "You can substitute evaporated milk for condensed milk, but it requires a few adjustments to achieve the same sweetness and consistency. Here's how:\n\n**The key difference:**\n\n*   **Condensed Milk:** Evaporated milk with sugar added. It's thick, sweet, and often used in desserts.\n*   **Evaporated Milk:** Milk that has about 60% of its water removed. It's unsweetened and has a slightly cooked flavor.\n\n**The Substitution Ratio & Process:**\n\nFor every **1 cup of condensed milk** in a recipe, use:\n\n*   **1 cup evaporated milk**\n*   **+ 1/2 cup granulated sugar**\n\n**Instructions:**\n\n1.  **Combine:** In a saucepan, combine the evaporated milk and sugar.\n2.  **Heat and Dissolve:** Heat over medium heat, stirring constantly, until the sugar is completely dissolved.  Do NOT boil.\n3.  **Cool:** Let the mixture cool completely before using it in your recipe. This will help it thicken slightly.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Consistency:** The homemade sweetened condensed milk made from evaporated milk will likely be slightly thinner than commercially produced sweetened condensed milk. This isn't usually a problem, but if you need a thicker consistency, you can simmer the mixture for a bit longer on very low heat, stirring constantly, until it thickens to your desired consistency. Be careful not to burn it.\n*   **Flavor:** The homemade version might not have the exact same flavor as store-bought condensed milk. Some people find it has a slightly less intense sweetness or a more pronounced evaporated milk flavor.\n*   **Adjust Sugar:** If you prefer a less sweet result, you can reduce the amount of sugar slightly. Start with a little less than 1/2 cup and taste.\n*   **Recipe Adjustments:** Be mindful of the liquid content in the overall recipe. If you're concerned about the slightly thinner consistency, consider reducing the amount of other liquids in the recipe by a tablespoon or two to compensate.\n* **Baking:** In some baked goods, the substitution works perfectly well without changing the recipe at all.\n\n**Example:**\n\nLet's say a recipe calls for 1 can (14 oz) of condensed milk.  A 12 oz can of evaporated milk is close enough in volume.\n\nYou would use:\n\n*   1 (12 oz) can of evaporated milk\n*   1/2 cup + 2 tablespoons granulated sugar.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\nEvaporated milk can be a good substitute for condensed milk in many recipes as long as you add the appropriate amount of sugar and adjust for any potential consistency differences.  It's a helpful option when you don't have condensed milk on hand or prefer to control the sugar content.\n",
